resourcetypes.name: Applications
resourcetypes.notes: Software application of any kind.

attributes.name: monitor
attributes.description: Whether this application is to be monitored.

resourcetypes.name: Asns
resourcetypes.notes: BGP Autonomous System Numbers. The UID should be the ASN, and the ´name´ should be its human-friendly tag.

resourcetypes.name: AwsAvailabilityZones
resourcetypes.notes: Global availability zones. UID = ZoneId

resourcetypes.name: AwsEc2Instances
resourcetypes.notes: UID = whatever makes sense for matching it to its discovered counterpart.

resourcetypes.name: AwsEc2Tags
resourcetypes.notes: UID = key

resourcetypes.name: AwsRegions
resourcetypes.notes: uid is the short code, e.g. APSE2

attributes.name: name
attributes.description: the AWS name for this region

resourcetypes.name: AwsSubnets
resourcetypes.notes: UID = whatever makes sense to you, for mapping this to its discovered counterpart.

attributes.name: mappubliciponlaunch
attributes.description: Indicates whether instances launched in this subnet receive a public IPv4 address.

attributes.name: subnetarn
attributes.description: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the subnet.

attributes.name: availableipaddresscount
attributes.description: The number of unused private IPv4 addresses in the subnet. The IPv4 addresses for any stopped instances are considered unavailable.

resourcetypes.name: AwsVpcAvailabilityZones
resourcetypes.notes: Mapping from this VPC to the global AZ. UID = ZoneName

resourcetypes.name: AwsVpcs
resourcetypes.notes: UID = Description is probably your best bet.

attributes.name: cidrblock
attributes.description: The primary IPv4 CIDR block for the VPC.

attributes.name: bgpPeerIdentifier
attributes.description: Index for the bgpPeerEntry SNMP table

attributes.name: monitor
attributes.description: Whether this peering is to be monitored.

resourcetypes.name: Cabinets
resourcetypes.notes: A frame for rack-mounting equipment in. May be in the form of a lockable

resourcetypes.name: Cages
resourcetypes.notes: Lockable areas within a room, containing racks. Usually found in data centres.

resourcetypes.name: Circuits
resourcetypes.notes: Network circuits, whether telco-provided or otherwise.

resourcetypes.name: DarkFibreLinks
resourcetypes.notes: Dark fibre network link, from one device to another

resourcetypes.name: DeviceRoles
resourcetypes.notes: Classification of the device, e.g. host, router or switch.

resourcetypes.name: DeviceTypes
resourcetypes.notes: Type of device, e.g. physical, cluster or virtual.

resourcetypes.name: Devices
resourcetypes.notes: Any kind of device that interacts with a network.

attributes.name: monitor
attributes.description: Whether this device is to be monitored.

resourcetypes.name: Environments
resourcetypes.notes: Development, testing, staging, production etc.

resourcetypes.name: Ipv4Interfaces
resourcetypes.notes: IPv4 address as configured on an interface

resourcetypes.name: Ipv6Interfaces
resourcetypes.notes: IPv6 address as configured on an interface

resourcetypes.name: Licenses
resourcetypes.notes: The license under which software (or possibly hardware) is made available.

attributes.name: description
attributes.description: A summary of the license in question

resourcetypes.name: LifeCyclePhases
resourcetypes.notes: Where the device currently is, in its lifecycle. E.g. ordered, installed, in service or decommissioned.

resourcetypes.name: Links
resourcetypes.notes: Generic segment or section of a network circuit.

attributes.name: bandwidth
attributes.description: The committed information rate for this link

resourcetypes.name: Makes
resourcetypes.notes: Also known as ´brand´.

attributes.name: description
attributes.description: Comments about this particular model version.

attributes.name: monitor
attributes.description: Whether this interface is to be monitored.

resourcetypes.name: Parts
resourcetypes.notes: Spare parts, swappable components, anything of the kind: hard drives, SFPs etc.

resourcetypes.name: Racks
resourcetypes.notes: The rack location within a cabinet where a device is mounted. Usually the topmost rack number, in the case of multi-unit-height hardware.

resourcetypes.name: RecommendedOsVersion
resourcetypes.notes: Version recommended for this make and model. Helpful when you're trying to converge on a standard.

attributes.name: mandatory
attributes.description: Whether this version is mandatory, or merely recommended.

resourcetypes.name: Rooms
resourcetypes.notes: Rooms within a floor or a building.

resourcetypes.name: ServiceLevels
resourcetypes.notes: Sets the expectations for responses to issues, e.g. gold, silver, bronze, plastic

resourcetypes.name: Sites
resourcetypes.notes: Like a campus, a site contains one or more buildings.

resourcetypes.name: VlanGroups
resourcetypes.notes: A notional VLAN, the sum of the VLANs of one or more devices. Often confused as being the VLAN itself.

resourcetypes.name: Vlans
resourcetypes.notes: Layer 2 spans, as configured on devices, i.e. ethernet segments. Not to be confused with subnets.

resourcetypes.name: VrfGroups
resourcetypes.notes: VRF Groups allocated for use

resourcetypes.name: Vrfs
resourcetypes.notes: VRFs as configured on devices

relationships.name: MEMBERS
relationships.notes: Indicates that this device is a member of that stack/cluster.

relationships.name: ROLE
relationships.notes: The role(s) being fulfulled by this device: e.g, a layer-3 switch should have the roles switch and router.

relationships.name: VENDOR
relationships.notes: The organisation from which this device was bought.

relationships.name: CAPABILITY
relationships.notes: The capabilities available from this model, regardless of whether you're using any/all of them right now.

relationships.name: RECOMMENDED_OS_VERSION
relationships.notes: For the simple case where there's a global preference within this instance of Syscat

relationships.name: CONNECTED_TO
relationships.notes: The simplest network link: direct from one interface to another.

relationships.name: MEMBER
relationships.notes: Denotes that an interface is associated with a VRF or routing instance.

relationships.name: MEMBERS
relationships.notes: This interface is a member of that etherchannel/port-channel/reth/aggregated-ethernet bundle.

relationships.name: SUBINTERFACES
relationships.notes: Also known as logical interfaces in Junos.

relationships.name: VLAN
relationships.notes: Associate a network interface with a VLAN, regardless of which way around the underlying OS sees the relationship.
